  <span id="freeText1887856883674547861" style="display:none">Reading Oriana Fallaci highlights the difficulty of separating art from the artist. I have my moral objections to reading Fallaci due to her pure, I-dare-say pathological, uncompromising hatred of Muslims as a group and Islam as a religion. This makes it very difficult for me to read and appreaciate her work separately from these opinions: I cannot help but feel as if what I am reading is informed by the same worldview that informed her hatred.<br /><br />Nonetheless, I decided to go through with reading this book because I do find it important to try and understand figures that have had in one way or another a lot of power in shaping public opinion. Furthermore, the book is actually a fascinating and informative piece of literature.<br /><br />In this book, Fallaci tells the story of the great love of her life, Alexander Panagulis, who attempted to assasinate the head of the Greek junta in 1968 and was subsequently imprisoned. After his release from prison 5 years later, Panagulis meets Fallaci and a whirlwind romance ensues - the passion is again, almost pathological.<br /><br />The first part of the book was exceedingly interesting. Panagulis' story, his capture, his time in prison, makes for a beautiful book all on its own. I would have given the first part of the book 5 stars in all honestly. However, the story later becomes, for lack of a better word, obsessive. The love between Fallaci and Panagulis is destructive, unhealthy, painful. While the book often reads as a letter of closure, where Fallaci does not hide his faults, it also reads as a letter of pardon, where she excuses his faults.. An emancipated woman, a war reporter, someone that was left for dead while covering a war, shows us that it is still possible to completely idolize someone you love because of what they believe in politically, even though what they act out personally may harm you. While this might seem like love, to me this mostly seems like the destruction of the self.<br /><br />In terms of structure: the story becomes too convoluted - it starts as a political drama, and romance is promised. However, too many never-fully-carried-to-term reflections on the political situation of the world, too many love betrayals, too many dissapointments are described. It reads as a cross between a publicist's work (which Fallaci has indeed mostly written) and an attempt at an epic work of fiction. It does not work out too well. Furthermore, it also does not reach its goal - Panagulis asks Fallaci to document his life as a testament of his work to the people of Greece, but instead, she writes this letter of closure/of apology/of love. Understandable, from a woman that has loved and lost, but what the book promises to be.</span>
